f American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Hewet</i>, <i>Huet</i>, <i>Hughet</i>, <i>Howet</i>, pet forms of <i>Hugh</i> (Middle English <i>Hewe</i>, <i>Hue</i>; see   Hugh   and compare   Hew  ). The spelling <i>Hughet</i> stood for both <i>Huet</i> and the synonymous <i>Huget</i>; see   Huggett  . This surname has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","habitational name from Hewitts in Chelsfield or Hewitts in Willesborough (both Kent), both named from Old English <i>hīewett</i> ‘cutting’, denoting a place where trees had been cut down. Here there lived families called <i>de la Hewatte</i> (1270), <i>de la hewett</i> (1301), and <i>atte Hewete</i> (1338). The name may also be topographic for someone who lived in a newly made clearing in a wood."],"variants":[{"name":"Howatt","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Hewatt","meanings":["English: variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Hewitson","meanings":["English (northern): patronymic from the personal name <i>Hewet</i>; see   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Howett","meanings":["English (East Midlands): variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Huett","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Hewitt  .","German (<b>Hütt</b>): status name for someone living in a hut or owning a small shop, Middle High German <i>hütte</i>, or a habitational name from any of several places called Hütt or Hütte. Compare   Hutt  ."]},{"name":"Hewett","meanings":["English: variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Howat","meanings":["Scottish (southwestern): variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Howitt","meanings":["English (East Midlands): variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]},{"name":"Huet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre.","English: variant of   Hewitt  .","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Hue   ‘Hugh’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Hewitt was born in 1321, in Walsall, West Midlands, England, United Kingdom as the son of John Hewitt. He married Catherine Bowles in 1348, in Walsall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1385, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1321–1385":"1321–1385","1328–1385":"1328–1385","1355–1382":"1355–1382","1365–1382":"1365–1382","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1348":"1348","about 1382":"umbes 1382","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","1365":"1365","1385":"1385","about 1365":"umbes 1365","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Baddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Baddington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Rushall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rushall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Walsall, Stafordshire, England":"Walsall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baddington, Cheshire, England":"Baddington, Cheshire, England","Walsall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Walsall, West Midlands, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1321–1385":"1321–1385","1328–1385":"1328–1385","1355–1382":"1355–1